  "prompt": "How can we check whether a number is prime or not?",
  "response": "To determine whether a number \\( n \\) is prime, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Understand the definition of prime numbers**: A prime number is a natural number greater than 1 that cannot be formed by multiplying two smaller natural numbers. In other words, it has exactly two distinct positive divisors: 1 and itself.\n\n2. **Basic checks**:\n   - If \\( n \\leq 1 \\), then it is not prime.\n   - If \\( n = 2 \\), it is prime (the only even prime number).\n   - If \\( n > 2 \\) and even, then it is not prime.\n\n3. **Trial division**: For odd numbers greater than 2, perform the following steps:\n   - Only check for factors up to \\( \\sqrt{n} \\). If \\( n \\) is not divisible by any prime number less than or equal to \\( \\sqrt{n} \\), then \\( n \\) is prime.\n   - Test divisibility by prime numbers starting from 3 and going up to \\( \\sqrt{n} \\) (3, 5, 7, 11, etc.). \n\nHere\u2019s a simple algorithm in pseudocode:\n\n```\nfunction isPrime(n):\n    if n <= 1:\n        return false\n    if n == 2:\n        return true\n    if n % 2 == 0:\n        return false\n    for i from 3 to sqrt(n) step 2:\n        if n % i == 0:\n            return false\n    return true\n```\n\n### Example\nTo check if 29 is prime:\n1. 29 is greater than 1.\n2. 29 is not even.\n3. Check divisibility by odd numbers: 3, 5 (up to \\( \\sqrt{29} \\approx 5.39 \\)):\n   - \\( 29 \\div 3 \\) does not yield an integer.\n   - \\( 29 \\div 5 \\) does not yield an integer.\n4. Since there are no divisors found, 29 is prime.\n\n### Additional methods\n- **Sieve of Eratosthenes**: For finding all prime numbers up to a certain limit, this algorithm iteratively marks the multiples of each prime starting from 2.\n- **Probabilistic tests**: For very large numbers, methods like the Miller-Rabin primality test or the Fermat primality test can be used, which are faster but may have a small probability of error.\n\nUsing these methods, you can effectively check if a number is prime!",
